Cabot Wealth Advisory - Thinking Big Vs. Thinking Small
May 14, 2007

The Vastness of the Vineyards

Looking for Huge Mass Markets

Put on Your Optimist's Hat


I'm writing this Wealth Advisory just one week removed from a truly
fantastic trip to California's wine country.  As a lover of lakefront
property, the best way I can describe it is this:  wine country (my fiancé
and I mainly stayed and toured in Sonoma, though one day we did explore
route 29 in Napa) has all the beauty and calming effect of any big lake
... except instead of a big body of water, you've got vineyards.  

If you've never been to this part of the U.S., you should definitely do
so, whether you know the difference between a Chardonnay (most popular
wine in the U.S.) and a Malbec (a former mixing grape that some wineries
are now using as drink in and of itself) or not.  

Hell, I'm anything but a wine connoisseur (I'm a bourbon man myself), and
this was one of my top vacations ever.  Just seeing and driving through
the huge hills with gorgeous green grass, acres of vineyards, and cute
country architecture will put a full seven-day smile on your face.  It's
nature at its best out there.

What was the most striking part of the trip?  One was the gas prices
($3.75 a gallon for the cheapest brand ... I kid you not!).  But the other
was the vastness of the vineyards ... they went on for miles and miles and
miles, in every direction, up and down hills and in regular folks'
backyards.  And when you're tasting at one of the larger wineries, you
(like us) might hear something like, "This wine you're tasting is one of
our limited releases; we made only 17,000 cases of it last year."  

"Only" 17,000 cases!  That's 204,000 bottles, and that's just one
limited-release vintage, from one winery among dozens in California. 
That's one heckuva lot of wine.  And it got me thinking about size and
scale, and how the ordinary person (like me in wine country) can't imagine
how big things are in the great wide world.

==

You see, we're all brought up in a certain environment, a certain world
that we're exposed to.  In my case, I was exposed to a couple hundred kids
my age, of generally middle- to upper-middle class life.  And I was taught
all the same worldly statistics as the rest of you - that there's six
billion people in the world, or that the U.S. produces more than $12
trillion worth of goods and services per year, etc.  But most people
(including me) can never really grasp the size of those types of figures. 
Our brains aren't programmed that way.

Which is one reason I believe the average investor has so much trouble in
the market.  When he or she encounters a new, revolutionary product that's
targeting a huge mass market, it's difficult to imagine just how big that
company could become.  Instead, we tend to artificially put limits on a
company's growth potential, believing that rapid growth may continue for a
little while ... but eventually, it'll be back to "normal."  

(Incidentally, a lot of people do the same thing with their own careers,
believing "it'll never get better than this."  And because they think that
way, it never does.  But I digress.)

Put another way, most investors tend to think small, instead of thinking
big.  And if you don't believe you'll ever make, say, 100% on a stock, you
never will. 

The obvious example of late has been the solar stocks, which we've written
about numerous times in the Wealth Advisory.  Currently, our favorite of
the bunch, First Solar (FSLR), sports a forward P/E ratio of nearly 140,
and sports a market capitalization of nearly $5 billion.  Expensive!  

But is it?  The company is growing at stunning rates (its first quarter
revenues nearly quintupled from the year before), and there are only so
many solar stocks to invest in.  Who knows how large the firm will become,
or how many states and countries will encourage solar power use?  And what
happens if solar becomes nearly cost-competitive with current electricity?
 How big could that market be?  This is what I mean by thinking big.

Another example is Crocs (CROX), one of our favorite stocks at the present
time.  (It's been in the Cabot Market Letter's Model Portfolio since early
last October.)  Sentiment surrounding this maker of "plastic shoes"
remains skeptical, with millions of shares sold short and most investors
awaiting the end of this so-called fad.  But I'm thinking this is no fad! 

Hey, I'm not saying Crocs will someday replace formal shoes.  But Crocs
does represent a new type of footwear, and there's no reason to think that
tens of millions of pairs won't be sold in the U.S. ... and hundreds of
millions overseas.  It's difficult to think in these huge figures, but
when you're dealing with a mass market, growth can astound.

In the latest two quarters, for instance, sales and earnings both rose
more than 200% from the year before, while margins swelled.  And analysts
- who are typically a conservative lot - are now looking for $3 a share in
earnings for 2007.  Just eight months ago, they were looking for half
that!

The only way you're going to capitalize on the market's biggest winners is
by first believing a stock is capable of rising 50%, 100% or more over a
period of months.  In other words, you need to think big!
====
