===
Back to the present market, I don't believe enough investors are truly
thinking big about the potential of this bull market.  Simply put, this
market is going to head higher ... much higher.

I say this because we've seen a slew of unique market timing signals that
only come around at the beginning of major bull moves.  Tim already
mentioned one in the Wealth Advisory six weeks ago:  the occurrence of two
9-to-1 volume up days (what we call the Volume Blast-Off Indicator) within
a one-month span.  Historically, when this occurs, the S&P 500 is up 6%
three months later, 12% six months later, and 18% a year later.

What else?  What about historically high short interest on the NYSE?  As
of the middle of April (short interest is reported once a month), shorts
have been super-active; when short interest has been this elevated in
years past, the S&P 500 is up more than 5% three months later, 10% six
months later and 18% a year later.  (Those figures sound familiar?)

And here's something that doesn't exactly produce buy signals, but is
interesting nonetheless.  We recently read that, if you take all of the
buy/hold/sell ratings from analysts on all the S&P 500 companies, just 47%
of those ratings are a "buy" of one sort or the other.  That's a ten-year
low (!!), telling you analysts are overly pessimistic.  Incidentally, back
in 2000, that figure was a huge 70%, a sign of euphoria.

Want more?  How about the fact that, since 1950 the Dow, on average, rises
50% from the low of the mid-term year of the President Cycle (i.e., 2006,
2002, 1998, etc.) to its high of the following year.  No joke!  Since the
Dow's 2006 low was 10,700, I believe Dow 15,000 or even 16,000 is possible
this year.

Of course, there will be corrections along the way ... some scary drops to
shake out the weak hands.  But overall, you should be thinking about how
you're going to make truly big money this year.  

One vehicle I wrote about before is still a good one:  ProShares, which
give you the opportunity to own a fund that moves twice the Dow (which,
believe it or not, is the strongest index in the market since the February
low), or the S&P 500, or the Russell 2000, and so on.  If the market's
going to make a big move, these ProShares will give you a relatively
low-risk (compared to a volatile growth stock) way to capture that move.  

But whatever your investment of choice, let me leave you with this
message:  Be an optimist, be a bull.  The odds heavily favor some great
upward movement in the market this year, so think big and give yourself a
chance to make big money.

All the best,

Mike Cintolo

